<<#
This is the canonical example poem: it exercises every syntax feature and
doubles as the golden test fixture. This comment block (and the preamble
variable definitions below) never appear in the output.
#>>

={author_name}=A Poet
={v2name}=song arrangement
={refrain}<<=
Sing it once, sing it twice
Sing the words of paradise
=>>

Example Poem
${author_name}
1970-01-31

{{ Version 1 }}  # version label (optional); this trailing comment is ignored

{Stanza 1}  # segment label (optional)
These are the lines
   with leading indentation preserved
of *stanza* one, with _emphasis_, **strong**, and ~struck~ words.
A "double-quoted" phrase and a `single-quoted` one,
an en--dash, an em---dash, an ampersand &, an apostrophe's tail.

{Stanza 2}
A [link|example.com] and a /.highlight{highlighted span},
with escaped \*asterisks\* and a literal \-\-\- triple-hyphen.
First line, with a hard line break here,  
and the line that follows it.

> A block-quoted couplet,
> two lines within one quote.

----  # divider between versions

{{ Version 2 (${v2name}) }}  # a variable used inside a label

{Verse 1}
${refrain}

{Verse with embedded table}
The structural beats are:
<<<markdown
| Section | Bars |
|---------|------|
| Verse   | 8    |
| Chorus  | 4    |
>>>
and the verse resumes after the table.

{Interactive note}
Raw HTML between bare <<< and >>> passes through untouched:
<<<
<button type="button" onclick="alert('Hi!')">Press me</button>
>>>

